ERROR/Strange Behaviour in the 'Working' set of REST requests
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
o First of all, the output of the REST commands aren't really very much as what
  Grant promises in the doc for FI-WARE.
  Plenty of time to fix that though ...
  Also, especially for logging (which is about the first that was implemented),
  the REST verb isn't very much looked at ... This must also be fixed.
  In the beginning we did everything with 'GET' ...

o 'logging'
  As output we get an initial 'No content in answer from REST client'.
  For the rest, this seems to work.
  But, there seems to be a problem for 'GET'.
  I only see the output from one cluster node ...

o 'cluster add' + 'cluster remove':
  The string 'cluster add/remove host:port' is sent as delilah-command but it doesn't seem to do what it should ...

o Asking for details for an operations with a dot in its name:
  % curl --request GET     localhost:1202/samson/operations/system.lines

  The default output is not XML, it comes out in plain text ...
  Not really a problem, adding '.xml' and it works at it should, but it is an inconsistency.
  If we say XML is the default output format, thrn it should be for all REST requests ...


o Asking for details for a queue that doesn't exist (actually two different):
  % curl --request GET     localhost:1202/samson/queues/inputXXX
  % curl --request GET     localhost:1202/samson/queues/inputXXX.aaa

  These two command give different results ...
  And they shouldn't

  Both should report 'queue "QNAME" does not exist', but ...

  'inputXXX' gives this output:
    <?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
    <!-- SAMSON Rest interface -->
    <samson>
    <error><![CDATA[No content in answer from REST client]]></error>
    </samson>

  'inputXXX.aaa' gives this:
    error:
    No content in answer from REST client

  It seems the latter has some kind of 'plain text' as format ...
  This is probably due to the change in 'if ('.json' | '.xml' || '.html' ...)
  There we set format as "" and should probably set it to 'xml', as default format .
  What about this 'plain text' format?
  Is there another suffix for it?


